  <h2>Why People Choose to Sell As-Is</h2>
  <p>Repairs are expensive, time-consuming, and stressful. Contractors don't always show up. Costs balloon. When you factor in the time and money of getting a house market-ready versus selling directly for cash, many homeowners come out ahead by skipping the process entirely.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>No repairs, cleaning, or prep work</li>
    <li>Leave furniture, junk, whatever you want</li>
    <li>No contractor delays or surprise costs</li>
    <li>Fast, certain close with no contingencies</li>
    <li>Fair offer based on as-is market value</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Honest Trade-Off</h2>
  <p>A cash offer will typically be below full retail market value — that's the trade-off for speed, certainty, and zero prep costs. But when you factor in commissions (5–6%), repair costs, carrying costs during a 60–90 day listing, and the risk of deals falling through — a fair cash offer often puts more money in your pocket than you'd expect.</p>
  <p>We'll always give you a straight answer. If the traditional route is actually better for your situation, we'll tell you that.</p>

